The dominant theory suggests that this ritual served to: 1. '''Deify the land''' through the worship of Ikushima and Tarushima. 2. '''Infuse the Emperor’s clothing with the spirit of the land (shamanistic soul-invitation)'''. 3. '''Symbolically transfer the land’s divine authority to the Emperor''', thereby reinforcing his '''sovereignty over the land'''.{{Sfn|八十島祭（国史）}}
Over time, the '''festival's nature changed''', and participation expanded to include '''the Empress's court (中宮使)''' and '''the Crown Prince's court (東宮使)'''. The '''procession''' became more extravagant, featuring '''elaborate displays and female attendants in luxurious attire'''. Notably, during '''Emperor Nijō's Yasoshima Festival''', '''Taira no Kiyomori's daughter''' served as the ritual envoy, forming a particularly grand procession.{{Sfn|新修大阪市史 本文編 第2巻|1988|pp=39-44}}
[[File:Ikukunitama-jinja haiden-2.JPG|thumb|220px|right|{{center|[[Ikukunitama Shrine]] ({{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府}}, {{ill|Osaka City|ja|大阪市}})}}{{small|A shrine dedicated to Ikushima-no-Kami and Tarushima-no-Kami.}}]] The '''ritual site''' at '''Naniwazu''' is associated with '''Ikukunitama Shrine (生國魂神社)''', which enshrines '''Ikushima-no-Kami and Tarushima-no-Kami''', suggesting a historical link between the two. The '''Engishiki''' further notes that '''offerings''' were made to the following local deities during the festival: - '''Sumiyoshi Kami (住吉神, at Sumiyoshi Taisha)''' - '''Ōyorokoro Kami (大依羅神, at Ōyorokoro Shrine)''' - '''Kaijin (海神, "Sea Gods", unknown)''' - '''Tarumi Kami (垂水神, at Tarumi Shrine)''' - '''Suminomichi Kami (住道神, at Nakatomi Sumuchi Shrine)'''{{Sfn|新修大阪市史 本文編 第2巻|1988|pp=39-44}}
Over time, the '''influence of Sumiyoshi Taisha grew''', and by '''Chōryaku 1 (1037)''', records indicate that '''Sumiyoshi Shrine officials successfully moved the festival site from "Kumakawa-jiri" to their own "Taiya-hama"'''. However, the original location of '''Kumakawa-jiri''' remains unknown.{{Sfn|新修大阪市史 本文編 第2巻|1988|pp=39-44}}
Archaeological findings from the '''Gotanjima Ruins (吹田市南吹田, Suita City, Minami-Suita)''' suggest a connection to the festival. Many '''ritual artifacts''', such as '''bronze mirrors and iron arrowheads''', have been unearthed from an ancient riverbed, but the '''absence of dolls or bronze bells''', as well as the fact that the site is '''inland rather than coastal''', has led some scholars to '''question the connection'''.<ref>*Ancient Port or Ritual Site? – Unraveling the Mystery of the Gotanjima Ruins*, Suita City Museum, 2016, pp. 38-39.</ref>
It is also known that many '''emperors prior to Emperor Kōnin (光仁天皇)''' visited '''Naniwa the year after their Daijōsai''', suggesting that the '''Yasoshima Festival may date back at least to the 7th century'''.{{Sfn|八十島祭（国史）}}{{Sfn|新修大阪市史 本文編 第1巻|1988|pp=595-599}} Some scholars even theorize that its origins may reach back to the '''5th century, during the Kawachi Dynasty (河内王朝)''', or that it was connected to '''Naniwa Palace (難波宮)'''.{{Sfn|新修大阪市史 本文編 第1巻|1988|pp=595-599}}{{Sfn|岡田精司|2011|pp=189-192}} == See Also == * [[Ikukunitama Shrine]]
